Issues.Body:
This is about the Bulma **Docs** 

The example JavaScript on https://bulma.io/documentation/components/modal/ has the following block:
<pre>// Add a keyboard event to close all modals
document.addEventListener('keydown', (event) => {
  if (event.code === 'Escape') {
    closeAllModals();
  }
});</pre>

This does not work on Chrome (118.0.5993.88) on a Mac (13.5.2)

I replaced it with:
<pre>// Add a keyboard event to close all modals
document.addEventListener("keydown",function(e){
  if(e.key === "Escape") {
    closeAllModals();
  }
});</pre>

I have tested this solution on Chrome and Firefox on a Mac and on Edge on Windows.

This is about **Bulma**. 

### Description

This is about the Bulma **CSS framework**. I'm using Bulma **version** 0.9.4.

Dropdown entries do not support a disabled state. Please add a method to create dropdown entries that are in a disabled state.

Neither `<a class="dropdown-item is-disabled">...</a>` nor `<a class="dropdown-item" disabled>...</a>` works.

### Example Solution:

```css
a.dropdown-item[disabled] {
    color: $grey;
    cursor: default;
    pointer-events: none;
}
```

As browsers are supporting nesting CSS, I am steering away from SCSS. I used to use the following SCSS code to customize Bulma styles:
```scss
$primary: #b78e6c;
$radius: 2px;
$input-focus-box-shadow-size: 0 0 0 0;
$button-focus-box-shadow-size: 0 0 0 0;
$navbar-breakpoint: 600px;
$card-shadow: 0px 2px 1px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2),
  0px 1px 1px 0px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.14), 0px 1px 3px 0px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.12);

@import "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/bulma@0.9.4/css/bulma.min.css";
```

Apparently these SCSS variables won't work with plain CSS. I wonder if there's any way I can customize Bulma styles with only CSS variables? Thanks.
